5.7    ESTABLISHMENT OF A RESPONSE MANAGEMENT SYSTEM



5.7.1     Emergency Response Coordinators (ERCs)



The Primary ERC and the Alternate ERC (in the absence of the Primary ERC) have complete authority to commit all available resources in the event of an emergency. The ERC and alternates are also responsible for emergency response coordination with state and local agencies on a 24-hour basis. Upon notification of an existing, imminent or potential emergency situation, the ERC will immediately identify the character, exact source, amount and extent (area) of the release or emergency by interviewing employees from the affected area, consulting with members of the emergency response team will be consulted, and examining appropriate emergency alarm panels.



Upon enactment of the emergency response plan, the ERC will be responsible for:



Mobilizing and directing of the Emergency Response Team;

Determining of the need for a plant evacuation;

Directing the emergency telephone operator to notify appropriate governmental agencies and off-site responders;

Providing information and support as necessary for off-site responders; and,

Documenting and reporting after an emergency situation.





5.7.2     Emergency Response Team



Emergency Response Team Members have the following responsibilities:



Notify the ERC once an emergency situation is discovered;

Identify and initiate plant alarms;

Mobilize at command center and follow instructions of the ERC;

Awareness and identification of the level of hazards or potential hazards which have caused or may cause an emergency situation;

Conduct an evacuation at

command post; and,

Location of the decontamination areas.





5.11       PROCEDURES FOR MOBILIZATION OF RESOURCES



After a briefing and discussion with the ERC, members of the emergency response team will be dispatched to the scene of the incident.  Personal protective equipment will be worn as appropriate. The location of the emergency response team members responding to the scene of the incident will be known as the Forward Command Post.  The Forward Command Post will maintain open communications with the EOC at all times.  The main objective of the initial response of the emergency response team will be to determine the extent of the incident, particularly regarding any possible personnel injuries.  Response to personnel injuries will be the top priority. The Forward Command Post will report to the EOC regarding the extent and current status of the incident. The ERC will then provide additional direction and guidance to the emergency response team.



5.12       SUSTAINED ACTIONS



ERC's Incident Checklist is used to document the following activities during the emergency:



Names of persons and agencies contacted, time contacted, description of conversation and report numbers issued;

Record of control measures taken, including times of action when possible;

Post operations;

Cleanup;

Log of emergency responders;

Log of detector readings; and,

Assignment sheet for the incident command system.





5.13     NATIONAL INCIDENT MANAGEMENT SYSTEM (NIMS)



The National Incident Management System (NIMS) is an emergency management principles used all over United States.  NIMS provides a systematic proactive guidelines to departments and agencies at all levels of government, non-governmental organizations, and the private sector to work, respond to, recover from and mitigate the effects of incidents, regardless of cause, , location, or complexity, in order to reduce the loss of life and property and harm to the environment. It is encourage to consider using the NIMS
